n <- 5
nsims <- 1000

# Define vector of sample means as a numeric vector and give it length equal to 'nsims'
xbars <- numeric(nsims)

# Take 1000 samples of size n and record means in the vector. The result is a vector containing 1000 sample means.
for(i in 1:nsims){
  
  xbars[i] <-mean(sample(pop1$V1,n,replace = FALSE))

zs<-(xbars-5)/(4/sqrt(n))
qqnorm(zs,main="xbars$Pop1")

My expectation is that the sample should be almost normally distributed with mean = 5 and standard deviation = 4 and variance = 16/5. From the plot,we can see that the curve is close to the y=x line.Thus,it matches my expectation and the sample from pop1 is a normal distribution.

#Your code here
n=5
sigma=4
length=10:400
nsims=391
vars=numeric(nsims)
for(i in 10:400){
  srsn=rnorm(i, mean=5,sd=4)
  vars[i]=var(sample(srsn,n,replace = FALSE))
}
qqnorm(vars,xlab = "standard deviation")
